My thoughts on using gml to write an outliner

Need to add online insert, edit and delete
    insert means adding a new group and because groups appear in bitmap order, it presents a problem. We can use an order attribute and then sortByAttribute. insert then means adding a group and inserting it in the parent list, probably best done using an insert method that we do not have yet.
    edit, assuming we are using a text field, mac does this for us but we need to make sure that the edited text is updated in the group. Or use an edit field, separate from the outline that gets filled in when you select an entry to edit - I like this idea, tho probably not commercially viable
    delete, probably can use the remove method but it will have to be updated to include list handling DONE
    cut and paste will be needed, can make this a delete then insert but have to keep the latest delete item

Not sure if setDetails will add the details for inserted group. Looks like it does. Have to test and see.
Initially can write the outline in gml the old fashioned way, using a text editor and have the outliner work mostly as a viewer, adding new capability as needed. That way we can test out the look and feel and add the ability to modify it online as we go; ie. outline is a tree

Add an outline attribute, as in outline=order where order is the name of the attribute that will define the outline order
    First time thru, when there may be no order attribute present, we inject one as we create the outline, hence we will need an outline method added to Bwana

Rather than use the tree model (too limited), try expand and collapse methods that work on a selected group. To collapse, turn noRoom on and replace with group tag in a cell sized to fit text. To expand, noRoom the tag and turn on the group.

Might be nice to recast this as a folding xml editor. That provided much of the utility of an outline but fits well w/GUI. I would add auto indenting extended to commands and coloring of text and comments. Maybe dispense w/bracing; use tag tab text (set to body of getTagXML). That would be simple but eliminates the interesting stuff in that you cannot see what the xml looks like. Really would prefer to have the xml actionable as gml.

